{"name": "write_file", "arguments": {"path": "src/utils/lru-cache.ts", "content": "/**
 * Least Recently Used (LRU) cache.
 * When the cache is full, the least recently accessed item is evicted.
 * Uses a Map for O(1) get/set — Map preserves insertion order,
 * so we delete and re-insert on access to move items to the end.
 */
export class LRUCache<K, V> {
  private cache = new Map<K, V>();
  private readonly maxSize: number;

  constructor(maxSize: number) {
    if (maxSize < 1) throw new Error('LRU cache size must be at least 1');
    this.maxSize = maxSize;
  }

  get(key: K): V | undefined {
    const value = this.cache.get(key);
    if (value === undefined) return undefined;

    // Move to end (most recently used)
    this.cache.delete(key);
    this.cache.set(key, value);
    return value;
  }

  set(key: K, value: V): void {
    // If key exists, delete first to update position
    if (this.cache.has(key)) {
      this.cache.delete(key);
    }

    // Evict oldest if at capacity
    if (this.cache.size >= this.maxSize) {
      const oldest = this.cache.keys().next().value;
      if (oldest !== undefined) this.cache.delete(oldest);
    }

    this.cache.set(key, value);
  }

  has(key: K): boolean {
    return this.cache.has(key);
  }

  delete(key: K): boolean {
    return this.cache.delete(key);
  }

  clear(): void {
    this.cache.clear();
  }

  get size(): number {
    return this.cache.size;
  }

  /** Iterate from oldest to newest */
  *entries(): IterableIterator<[K, V]> {
    yield* this.cache.entries();
  }
}
"}}
```

Created `src/utils/lru-cache.ts` — O(1) get and set using a trick with JavaScript's `Map`.

**Why this works:** `Map` preserves insertion order. When you `get` a key, we delete and re-insert it, moving it to the end. The oldest item is always `map.keys().next()` — the first entry. No linked list needed.

Usage:
```ts
const cache = new LRUCache<string, User>(100);
cache.set('user:123', user);
const cached = cache.get('user:123'); // Moves to most-recent
// When 101st item is added, the least-recently-used item is evicted
```

This is the same approach Redis uses internally for its LRU eviction, just simplified.

