{"name":"write_file","arguments":{"path":"src/orders/order.aggregate.ts","content":"// Event sourcing: state is derived by replaying events, not stored directly.
// The event log is the source of truth; the in-memory state is a projection.

export type OrderEvent =
  | { type: 'OrderCreated'; customerId: string; at: string }
  | { type: 'ItemAdded'; productId: string; qty: number; unitCents: number; at: string }
  | { type: 'OrderConfirmed'; at: string }
  | { type: 'OrderCancelled'; reason: string; at: string };

export interface OrderState {
  id: string;
  customerId: string;
  items: Array<{ productId: string; qty: number; unitCents: number }>;
  status: 'pending' | 'confirmed' | 'cancelled';
  totalCents: number;
}

export class Order {
  private events: OrderEvent[] = [];
  state: OrderState;

  private constructor(id: string, events: OrderEvent[]) {
    this.state = { id, customerId: '', items: [], status: 'pending', totalCents: 0 };
    this.events = events;
    events.forEach(e => this.apply(e));
  }

  static create(id: string, customerId: string): Order {
    const order = new Order(id, []);
    order.record({ type: 'OrderCreated', customerId, at: new Date().toISOString() });
    return order;
  }

  static rehydrate(id: string, events: OrderEvent[]): Order {
    return new Order(id, events);
  }

  addItem(productId: string, qty: number, unitCents: number): void {
    if (this.state.status !== 'pending') throw new Error('Cannot modify a ' + this.state.status + ' order');
    this.record({ type: 'ItemAdded', productId, qty, unitCents, at: new Date().toISOString() });
  }

  confirm(): void {
    if (!this.state.items.length) throw new Error('Cannot confirm empty order');
    this.record({ type: 'OrderConfirmed', at: new Date().toISOString() });
  }

  cancel(reason: string): void {
    if (this.state.status === 'cancelled') throw new Error('Already cancelled');
    this.record({ type: 'OrderCancelled', reason, at: new Date().toISOString() });
  }

  private record(event: OrderEvent): void {
    this.events.push(event);
    this.apply(event);
  }

  private apply(event: OrderEvent): void {
    switch (event.type) {
      case 'OrderCreated': this.state.customerId = event.customerId; break;
      case 'ItemAdded':
        this.state.items.push({ productId: event.productId, qty: event.qty, unitCents: event.unitCents });
        this.state.totalCents += event.qty * event.unitCents;
        break;
      case 'OrderConfirmed': this.state.status = 'confirmed'; break;
      case 'OrderCancelled': this.state.status = 'cancelled'; break;
    }
  }

  pendingEvents(): OrderEvent[] { return [...this.events]; }
}
"}}
```

Created `src/orders/order.aggregate.ts`. In event sourcing, you never update a row — you append an event. To load an aggregate, fetch its events from the store and replay them through `apply()` to rebuild state.

The separation of `record()` and `apply()` is intentional: `record` is called for new events (writing path), `apply` handles both new events and historical events during rehydration. This keeps the state-mutation logic in one place.

The discriminated union `OrderEvent` means TypeScript will error if you add a new event type but forget to handle it in the `switch` — exhaustiveness checking catches missing cases at compile time.

```ts
const order = Order.create(id, customerId);
order.addItem('prod-1', 2, 1999);
order.confirm();
// Save order.pendingEvents() to your event store
```

